  background: ;
  dark: ;
  size: ;
-->

<h2 id="evolutionary-history-of-tandem-running-behavior">Evolutionary history of tandem running behavior</h2>

<div class="float" data-flip="">
  
<figure class="figure">
  <a class="figure-image" aria-label="Tandem run of six termite species">
    <img src="/images/tandem_comp.gif" style="
        width: 250px;
        max-height: unset;
      " alt="Tandem run of six termite species" loading="lazy" onerror="this.src = '/images/fallback.svg'; this.onerror = null;" />
  </a>
  
    <figcaption class="figure-caption">
      Tandem run of six termite species

    </figcaption>
  
</figure>


</div>

<p>Tandem running is the simplest collective behavior. In termites, a pair of a female and a male coordinate their motion while exploring the environments. Leader females and follower males play <a href="https://doi.org/10.1126/sciadv.aau6108">their own roles to maintain coordination</a>. Even this simple behavior holds a great diversity of behavioral rules <a href="https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.2212401119">across phylogeny of termites</a> and <a href="https://doi.org/10.1098/rspb.2021.0998">between closely related species</a>. We try to expand to idea of simple tandem runs to more complex collective motion by a large group. We also study <a href="https://doi.org/doi:10.1016/j.isci.2023.106418">ant tandem runs</a>. <br />
<br />
â€”<a href="topics-tandem"><i class="icon fa-solid fa-bugs"></i> Click here to learn more.</a></p>

