<h2 id="comparative-analysis-of-termtie-building-structures">Comparative analysis of termtie building structures</h2>

<div class="float" data-flip="">
  
<figure class="figure">
  <a class="figure-image" aria-label="Tunneling structures of three different termite species. See [program](https://github.com/nobuaki-mzmt/tmanual)">
    <img src="/images/output.gif" style="
        width: 400px;
        max-height: unset;
      " alt="Tunneling structures of three different termite species. See [program](https://github.com/nobuaki-mzmt/tmanual)" loading="lazy" onerror="this.src = '/images/fallback.svg'; this.onerror = null;" />
  </a>
  
    <figcaption class="figure-caption">
      Tunneling structures of three different termite species. See <a href="https://github.com/nobuaki-mzmt/tmanual">program</a>

    </figcaption>
  
</figure>


</div>

<p>The structures built by social insects vary widely in pattern and complexity. How do these variations arise from individual behavior? Nest structures function at the group level, but these structures are outcomes of individual behavior. Thus, one needs to know the <a href="https://doi.org/doi:10.1086/711020">mechanical relationship between individual behavior and group-level structures</a>. We compare termite tunneling behavior across all termite lineages to trace back the evolution.<br /><br /></p>

<p>â€”<a href="topics-nest"><i class="icon fa-solid fa-tree"></i> Click here to learn more.</a></p>

